<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter xml:id="ch12-qft" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Quantum Field Theory Basics</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>Quantum Field Theory (QFT) is the union of quantum mechanics and special relativity. Fields are the fundamental entities; particles are excitations. This chapter covers canonical quantization, the interaction picture, Feynman diagrams, and renormalization—the essential tools of modern particle physics and condensed matter theory.</p>
  </introduction>
  <section xml:id="sec-ch12-scalar">
    <title>Quantizing the Scalar Field</title>
    <p>The free scalar field satisfies the Klein-Gordon equation. Quantization replaces the field with an operator,</p>
    <me>
      \hat{\phi}(x) = \int \frac{d^3p}{(2\pi)^3 \sqrt{2E_p}} (a_p e^{ip \cdot x} + a_p^\dagger e^{-ip \cdot x}),
    </me>
    <p>where <m>a_p</m> and <m>a_p^\dagger</m> are annihilation and creation operators. The vacuum state <m>|0\rangle</m> has no particles; <m>a_p^\dagger |0\rangle</m> creates one particle with momentum <m>p</m>.</p>
  </section>
  <section xml:id="sec-ch12-interactions">
    <title>Interactions and Perturbation Theory</title>
    <p>Interactions are encoded in the interaction Hamiltonian <m>H_I = \int d^3x \, \mathcal{L}_I(\phi)</m>. Perturbation theory gives the S-matrix,</p>
    <me>
      S = 1 + \frac{-i}{\hbar} \int dt \, H_I(t) + \cdots,
    </me>
    <p>which computes scattering amplitudes and transition rates.</p>
  </section>
  <section xml:id="sec-ch12-feynman">
    <title>Feynman Diagrams</title>
    <p>Feynman diagrams are a visual language encoding the S-matrix. External lines are particles; internal lines are virtual particles; vertices are interactions. Each diagram corresponds to an integral with a definite prescription.</p>
  </section>
  <section xml:id="sec-ch12-summary">
    <title>Chapter Summary</title>
    <ul>
      <li>Quantum fields are operator-valued distributions; particles are field excitations.</li>
      <li>Creation and annihilation operators build the Fock space of many-particle states.</li>
      <li>Interactions generate the S-matrix and scattering amplitudes via perturbation theory.</li>
      <li>Feynman diagrams encode amplitudes graphically and computationally.</li>
      <li>QFT unifies quantum mechanics and relativity, foundational for particle physics.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>
</chapter>
